				\begin{document}$${{{\mathrm{ICP}}}} = {{{\mathrm{FR}}}}_{{{{\mathrm{CSF}}}}}\;{{{\mathrm{x}}}}\;{{{R}}}_{{{{\mathrm{out}}}}} + {{{\mathrm{TCBF}}}}\;{{{\mathrm{x}}}}\;{{{R}}}_{{{{\mathrm{ven}}}}} + {{{\mathrm{JBP}}}}$$\end{document}ICP=FRCSFxRout+TCBFxRven+JBPwhere TCBF is the total blood flow leaving the capillaries to enter the venous system, Rven is the venous outflow resistance from the sagittal sinus to the jugular bulbs and JBP is the jugular bulb pressure. The CSF formation rate is normal in IIH and decreases as the ICP increases9. The pressure gradient between the CSF and sagittal sinus was found to low-normal at 2.34 mmHg in one paper in IIH10 and 2.7 mmHg in another11. Rearranging Eq. (1) by subtraction, the ICP to sagittal sinus pressure gradient is equal to the FRcsf x Rout, and if this term is normal, then the elevation in ICP in IIH can only be due to elevated venous pressure. This discussion tends to validate the original assertion made by Karahalios et al. i.e. “an elevated venous pressure is the universal mechanism underlying IIH”12. Is a venous pressure elevation also the universal cause of SANS?
